    passage: "Several artworks found among the ruins of the ancient Roman city of Pompeii depict a female figure fishing with a cupid nearby. Some scholars have asserted that the figure is the goddess Venus, since she is known to have been linked with cupids in Roman culture, but University of Leicester archaeologist Carla Brain suggests that cupids may have also been associated with fishing generally. The fact that a cupid is shown near the female figure, therefore, _____________",
    question: "Which choice most logically completes the text?",
    choices: ["is not conclusive evidence that the figure is Venus.","suggests that Venus was often depicted fishing.","eliminates the possibility that the figure is Venus.","would be difficult to account for if the figure is not Venus."],
    correct: 0,
    explanation: "<strong>Key Clues in the Passage</strong><br>The passage contrasts two possibilities: cupids were linked with Venus, but they \"may have also been associated with fishing generally.\" If a cupid can appear for multiple reasons, its presence cannot prove the woman is Venus.<br><br><strong>Working Through Each Choice:</strong><br><strong>(A)</strong> ✓ This matches the logic that a cupid nearby is suggestive but not definitive identification evidence.<br><strong>(B)</strong> ✗ The text never claims Venus was \"often depicted fishing\"; it only discusses one motif. <em>(No textual support)</em><br><strong>(C)</strong> ✗ The passage does not rule Venus out; it only says cupid evidence is inconclusive. <em>(Too extreme)</em><br><strong>(D)</strong> ✗ This reverses the point by treating the cupid as hard proof of Venus despite the alternative fishing association. <em>(Reverses the logic)</em><br><br><strong>Correct Answer: A</strong><br>This tests whether you can weigh competing explanations and avoid treating ambiguous evidence as conclusive proof."
