    choices: ["the greater importance assigned to delivery time and tracking than to package design may not be observed if the survey were to be given to a larger group of Serbian participants.","customers in countries with higher levels of economic development than that of Serbia are likely to regard package design as relatively more important than delivery time and transparency.","additional research is needed with participants from countries of varying levels of economic development to determine whether delivery time and tracking are more important than package design to customers broadly.","online retailers that operate in a variety of countries are more likely to increase customer loyalty if they make their deliveries in less time and allow customers to track those deliveries than if they improve their packaging."],
    correct: 2,
    explanation: "<strong>Key Clues in the Passage</strong><br>All respondents were from one country, Serbia, described as a \"developing economy.\" The warning about not generalizing means the sample may not represent customers in other economic contexts.<br><br><strong>Working Through Each Choice:</strong><br><strong>(C)</strong> ✓ This directly follows from the limited sample and the stated caution about broad application.<br><strong>(B)</strong> ✗ This predicts a specific pattern for richer countries that the study did not establish. <em>(Introduces unsupported idea)</em><br><strong>(A)</strong> ✗ The caution concerns cross-country generalization, not Serbian sample size alone. <em>(Misreads passage)</em><br><strong>(D)</strong> ✗ The researchers explicitly cautioned against this broad business recommendation. <em>(Goes beyond the text)</em><br><br><strong>Correct Answer: A</strong><br>This tests external validity reasoning: identify why a finding from one population may not generalize."
