    explanation: "<strong>Key Clues in the Passage</strong><br>Allen says \"the strongest judicial opinions consider and rebut potential objections.\" Engaging opposing philosophers would strengthen reasoning by testing and refining arguments.<br><br><strong>Working Through Each Choice:</strong><br><strong>(A)</strong> ✗ Discussing philosophers with conflicting views still requires engaging philosophical works, not avoiding them. <em>(Contradicts passage)</em><br><strong>(C)</strong> ✓ Rebutting objections directly improves argumentative rigor in opinions.<br><strong>(B)</strong> ✗ The claim is about argumentative strength, not ease for lay readers. <em>(Out of scope)</em><br><strong>(D)</strong> ✗ Allen discusses quality of reasoning, not aligning with majority philosophical opinion. <em>(No textual support)</em><br><br><strong>Correct Answer: B</strong><br>This tests whether you can infer function: considering counterarguments improves the quality of a claim."
