    correct: 1,
    explanation: "<strong>Key Clues in the Passage</strong><br>If founding is truly fourteenth century but some artifacts are thirteenth century, those older artifacts must predate settlement occupation at that site. A logical reconciliation is that they arrived from elsewhere later.<br><br><strong>Working Through Each Choice:</strong><br><strong>(A)</strong> ✗ Relative frequency of artifact dates does not resolve the dating conflict. <em>(Out of scope)</em><br><strong>(B)</strong> ✓ This explains how older artifacts can be present despite a later founding date.<br><strong>(C)</strong> ✗ Nothing in the evidence addresses founders' regional origin. <em>(No textual support)</em><br><strong>(D)</strong> ✗ Possible excavation damage does not account for thirteenth-century artifacts at a fourteenth-century settlement. <em>(Misreads passage)</em><br><br><strong>Correct Answer: B</strong><br>This tests reconciliation reasoning: identify the assumption that allows two apparently conflicting facts to coexist."
