    correct: 1,
    explanation: "<strong>Key Clues in the Passage</strong><br>Modern Rio Grande turkeys partly descend from Mesa Verde cultivated turkeys, and shared markers appear \"only after 1280,\" right after late-1200s dispersal. That pattern supports movement of people and husbandry practices.<br><br><strong>Working Through Each Choice:</strong><br><strong>(A)</strong> ✗ Genetic transfer evidence does not establish broader terrain similarity. <em>(Out of scope)</em><br><strong>(B)</strong> ✓ This directly fits timing, dispersal, and turkey lineage transfer.<br><strong>(C)</strong> ✗ The data do not prove Rio Grande peoples did not cultivate turkeys earlier. <em>(Too extreme)</em><br><strong>(D)</strong> ✗ The evidence points from Mesa Verde outward, not adoption into Mesa Verde from elsewhere. <em>(Reverses the logic)</em><br><br><strong>Correct Answer: B</strong><br>This tests historical inference from genetic and chronological evidence."
