    correct: 0,
    explanation: "<strong>Key Clues in the Passage</strong><br>Orangutans are observed using two-legged posture in trees while foraging, showing an arboreal context where bipedal stance can be useful. That observation supports a tree-based adaptive pathway for bipedalism.<br><br><strong>Working Through Each Choice:</strong><br><strong>(A)</strong> ✓ This is the best-supported implication of bipedal behavior providing arboreal advantage.<br><strong>(B)</strong> ✗ The evidence does not require simultaneous evolution of multiple locomotion modes. <em>(Too extreme)</em><br><strong>(C)</strong> ✗ The passage does not claim bipedalism was necessary for ground-tree movement. <em>(Overstates claim)</em><br><strong>(D)</strong> ✗ The point introduces a specific knuckle-walking ancestor ability not shown by the observations. <em>(Introduces unsupported idea)</em><br><br><strong>Correct Answer: A</strong><br>This tests hypothesis revision: new comparative behavior can support an alternative evolutionary scenario."
