    explanation: "<strong>Key Clues in the Passage</strong><br>If it is hard to count the population reliably, then changes in numbers under each strategy are hard to measure accurately. That uncertainty threatens valid conclusions about which strategy works best.<br><br><strong>Working Through Each Choice:</strong><br><strong>(A)</strong> ✗ The passage does not indicate methodological diffusion to other conservationists. <em>(No textual support)</em><br><strong>(C)</strong> ✓ This is the direct consequence of uncertain baseline and trend measurement.<br><strong>(B)</strong> ✗ Including more species is not the issue identified in the passage. <em>(Out of scope)</em><br><strong>(D)</strong> ✗ The concern raised is counting difficulty, not omission of lesser-known strategies. <em>(Misreads passage)</em><br><br><strong>Correct Answer: B</strong><br>This tests methodological inference: poor measurement precision can undermine causal evaluation of interventions."
